Why do we need intern()?

When we create a String using new, it creates a separate object in Heap memory.

intern() helps to:

Move that string reference to String Pool

Or return the already existing pooled reference

🔹 Example Without intern()
String s1 = new String("Java");
String s2 = "Java";

System.out.println(s1 == s2);   // false

Why?

s1 → Heap object

s2 → SCP object

Different memory references

🔹 Example With intern()
String s1 = new String("Java");
String s2 = "Java";

s1 = s1.intern();

System.out.println(s1 == s2);   // true

Now:

intern() returns reference from SCP

Both point to same memory

== becomes true ✅
